                    h1.page-header Rotational Kinetic Energy
                    p
                      | When we consider a rotating object, we are able to calculate the total kinetic energy associated with the rotational mass of all of the particles within the rotating object:
                    p
                      | $$ K_R = \sum K_i = \sum \frac{1}{2} m_i v^{2}_{i} = \frac{1}{2} \sum m_i r^{2}_{i} \omega^{2} $$
                    p $$ = \frac{1}{2} \left( \sum m_i r^{2}_{i} \right) \omega^2 $$
                    p where the variables in the brackets are called the moment of inertia:
                    p $$ I = \sum m_i r^{2}_{i} $$
                    p
                      | This can be though of as rotational mass, since it palys the same role for rotation that mass does in non-rotational motion.
                    p In terms of moment of intertia, the rotational kinetic energy can be expressed:
                    p $$ K_R = \frac{1}{2} I \omega^2 $$
                    p which is analogous to translational kinetic energy.
                    p
                      | One important observation is that the moment of intertia depends both on the amount of mass and on how far from the axis the mass is located.
                    p Common equations for various common moments of intertia can be found follow.
                    p Hoop or cylindrical sheel around axis:
                    p $$ M R^2 $$
                    p Solid cylinder or disk:
                    p $$ \frac{1}{2} M R^2 $$
                    p Rod about perpendicular axis through centre:
                    p $$ \frac{1}{12} M R^2 $$
                    p Rod about perpendicular axis through end:
                    p $$ \frac{1}{3} M R^2 $$
                    p Rectangular plate \( a \times b \) about perpendicular axis through center:
                    p $$ \frac{1}{2} M ( a^2 + b^2 ) $$
                    p Solid sphere:
                    p $$ \frac{2}{5} M R^2 $$
                    p Spherical shell:
                    p $$ \frac{2}{3} M R^2 $$
                    p
                      | The total kinetic energy of a rolling object is equal to the kinetic energy of translation of the center of mass, plus the kinetic energy of rotation about the center of mass:
                    p $$ KE = \frac{1}{2} I_{CM} \omega^2 +\frac{1}{2} M v^2 $$
